# Prereqs

Don&#39;t worry if you don&#39;t have all of these yet!

- Docker for Windows
- SQL Server 2017 Docker image.
- Azure CLI for PowerShell.
- SQL Server Management Studio.
- Postman.

# Getting started

You can do this while Bernard is talking if necessary.

- $ git clone https://github.com/bernardoleary/Azure-Bootcamp-2018.git
- Install Docker for Windows (D4W) – shouldn&#39;t take too long: [https://docs.docker.com/docker-for-windows/install/](https://docs.docker.com/docker-for-windows/install/)

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Make sure that you have enabled shared access across your drives:

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

- Get the SQL Server 2017 image – might take a little while:

$ docker pull microsoft/mssql-server-linux:2017-latest

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

- Confirm download:

$ docker images

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

- Install the Azure CLI: [https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/cli/azure/install-azure-cli-windows?view=azure-cli-latest](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/cli/azure/install-azure-cli-windows?view=azure-cli-latest)

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

- Make sure you have Visual Studio Tool for Docker installed: [https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/standard/containerized-lifecycle-architecture/design-develop-containerized-apps/visual-studio-tools-for-docker](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/standard/containerized-lifecycle-architecture/design-develop-containerized-apps/visual-studio-tools-for-docker)
- Make sure you have SSMS installed: [https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/sql/ssms/download-sql-server-management-studio-ssms?view=sql-server-2017](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/sql/ssms/download-sql-server-management-studio-ssms?view=sql-server-2017)

# Workshop 1 – Inventory &quot;microservice&quot; on Docker

We&#39;re going to build an extremely simple microservice (hence the quotation marks) using Docker for Windows, Docker Compose and SQL Server 2017 on Docker. Then we&#39;re going to populate it using Postman.

## Run a SQL Server container

1. Run the SQL image – create a container (change the port if you have a default SQL Server instance running on your machine already):

$ docker run -e &quot;ACCEPT\_EULA=Y&quot; -e &quot;MSSQL\_SA\_PASSWORD=P@ssw0rd&quot; -p 1433:1433 --name sql1 -d microsoft/mssql-server-linux:2017-latest

1. Verify the container is running:

$ docker ps

$ docker container ls

1. Log in to the DB server:

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

1. Run the SQL script to create the InventoryDB: [https://gist.github.com/bernardoleary/faf1e515d40f38db7fcf2aeb29bb4a3b](https://gist.github.com/bernardoleary/faf1e515d40f38db7fcf2aeb29bb4a3b)

Populate the InventoryDB with some stuff manually if you like.

## Get an API going

1. Get the code for the demo solution:

$ git clone

1. Take a look at Startup.cs – especially if you have not used dotnet core much in the past, note the baked-in IoC management (IServiceCollection). Also note the database connection details.
2. Run the solution and browse to the DB controller:

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

1. Now we can populate the DB using Postman:

{&quot;id&quot;:4,&quot;name&quot;:&quot;pineapples&quot;,&quot;quantity&quot;:20000}

[http://localhost:53346/api/database](http://localhost:53346/api/database)

Content-Type application/json

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

1. Note that this solution is not running as a container – it is on IIS Express – but the database is on a container.

## Add Docker Support

1. Now add &quot;Docker Support&quot; to the dotnet core project:

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Target Linux (because our SQL Server container is running on Linux also):

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

This will add another project to your solution called &quot;docker-compose&quot;. Note that your debug options have changed to &quot;Docker&quot; only (&quot;IISExpress&quot; is gone). Also a file called &quot;Dockerfile&quot; has been added to your dotnet core project.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

1. Run the Docker-ised solution in debug mode.

What happens when you try to reach [http://localhost:&lt;port&gt;/api/values](http://localhost:%3cport%3e/api/values)?

What happens when you try to reach [http://localhost: &lt;port&gt;/api/database](http://localhost:32769/api/database)?

1. Go to your PowerShell prompt and run:

$ docker image ls

This will list all images – note that there are two new images there now – one for your application and one for microsoft/aspnetcore:

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Docker has downloaded the microsoft/aspnetcore image because it is required to run our dotnet core web application – this is specified in the Dockerfile (take a look).

1. Now list your running containers:

$ docker image ls

You should see there are two containers running – one is out SQL DB, the other is our dotnet core web application:

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Why can the web-app not see the DB? Remember that Docker is like a miniature datacentre running on your PC – complete with networks. You can inspect the networks and see what containers are running on them:

$ docker network ls

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

$ docker network inspect &lt;network id&gt;

Unless it is told to, Docker will not put containers on the same network – hence why our containers aren&#39;t able to see each other.

## Take a copy of the DB and reset

1. Because Docker images are stateless, when we create a container from one it will spawn from scratch (a blank DB server) – so to avoid having to recreate the DB, we take a copy of the running container and commit it as an image – like this (get the container ID by running a &quot;$ docker ps&quot;):

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

$ docker image ls

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

1. Stop debugging and clear out all containers:

$ docker stop $(docker ps -a -q)

$ docker rm $(docker ps -a -q)

Check that no containers are running:

$ docker ps

## Add docker-compose support

1. Open the file named docker-compose.yml. Note that only our web-app&#39;s container is listed. We need to start the inventory container at the same time using docker-compose so that they containers are on the same network. Add the highlighted lines to the docker file:

version: &#39;3&#39;

services:

  dockerdemo.api:

    image: dockerdemoapi

    build:

      context: .

      dockerfile: DockerDemo.Api/Dockerfile

  dockerdemodb:

    image: inventorydb

1. Open Startup.cs and change the following line of code:

Environment.GetEnvironmentVariable(&quot;SQLSERVER\_HOST&quot;) ?? &quot; dockerdemodb&quot;;

1. Run the solution in debug mode again and try to reach the &quot;/api/database&quot; endpoint. Run a &quot;$ docker ps&quot; to see that you have your two containers The API container can now look up the hostname dockerdemodb and get back that container&#39;s IP address. Same goes for any other container we run as part of this solution using docker-compose.

# Workshop 2 – Push the Inventory microservice to AKS

We&#39;re going to make a Docker Hub account, push our Docker images to Docker Hub and finally we&#39;ll launch them to managed Kubernetes on Azure (AKS).

## Deploy an AKS cluster

1. Open PowerShell and login to Azure:

$ az login

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Set our subscription ID:

$ az account set  --subscription &quot;&lt;subscription id&gt;&quot;

1. Create a new Resource Group for this workshop, which we&#39;ll put the K8s (K8s is short for Kubernetes) cluster on – note, the Resource Group must be in eastus or another region that support the AKS preview:

$ az group create -l eastus -n ABC- K8s

1. Create our K8s cluster – this will take about 10-to-15 minutes:

$ az acs create -n ABC-Kube-Cluster -d ABC-Kube -g ABC-K8s --generate-ssh-keys --orchestrator-type kubernetes --agent-count 1 --agent-vm-size Standard\_D1\_v2

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Once you see the &quot;Running ..&quot; prompt you should be able to see the cluster deploying on the Azure portal:

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

## Set up your Docker Hub account

1. Go to [https://hub.docker.com](https://hub.docker.com) and sign-up – too easy!

## Make a release build of the microservice API

1. Go back to VS and change your build mode to &quot;Release&quot; and re-run our microservice:

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Note that once the build/run is completed that there is a new tag in our dockerdemoapi image tagged &quot;latest&quot;. Previously we only had one image in the repo, with a &quot;dev&quot; tag:

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

1. Test that the microservice works by changing our docker-compose.yml and docker-compose.override.yml file subtly to match our new images and running &quot;$ docker-compose up&quot; and/or running the release build in VS:

**docker-compose.override.yml**

version: &#39;3&#39;

services:

  dockerdemoapi:

    environment:

      - ASPNETCORE\_ENVIRONMENT=Development

    ports:

      - &quot;80&quot;

**docker-compose.yml**

version: &#39;3&#39;

services:

  dockerdemoapi:

    image: &lt;your docker hub namespace&gt;/dockerdemoapi

    build:

      context: .

      dockerfile: DockerDemo.Api/Dockerfile

  dockerdemodb:

    image: &lt;your docker hub namespace&gt;/inventorydb

1. Using the Docker &quot;ps&quot; and &quot;commit&quot; commands, make copies of your images that are prefixed with the namespace that you have created for your Docker Hub profile.

Docker Hub namespace – my one is &quot;abcdockerdemo&quot;:

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Commit command to make images that are prefixed with your Docker Hub namespace:

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

## Push your images to Docker Hub

1. Login to Docker:

$ docker login

1. Push your images to Docker Hub:

$ docker push &lt;your docker hub namespace&gt;/dockerdemoapi:latest

$ docker push &lt;your docker hub namespace&gt;/inventorydb:latest

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

You should be able to see your new repos on Docker Hub when you have finished:

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

## Set up the KubeCtl tool

1. Make a folder called &quot;kubectl&quot; under your &quot;C:\&quot; then run:

$ az acs kubernetes install-cli --install-location=C:\kubectl\kubectl.exe

1. Put kubectl on your PATH:

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

1. Get the key that will enable you to interact directly with AKS from the command line:

$ az acs kubernetes get-credentials --resource-group=ABC-K8s --name=ABC-Kube-Cluster

You should see the output as follows:

Merged &quot;k8s-kubemgmt&quot; as current context in C:\Users\bernardo\.kube\config

1. Start the kubectl proxy:

$ kubectl proxy

You should see output as follows: &quot;Starting to serve on 127.0.0.1:8001&quot;

Browse to [http://localhost:8001/ui](http://localhost:8001/ui)

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

## Deploy our microservice to AKS

1. Add a deployment file that we will use to upload to Kubernetes – I called mine dockerdemo.yml:

apiVersion: extensions/v1beta1

kind: Deployment

metadata:

  name: abcdockerdemo-deployment

spec:

  replicas: 3

  template:

    metadata:

      labels:

        app: abcdockerdemo

    spec:

      containers:

      - name: dockerdemoapi

        image: &lt;your docker hub namespace&gt;/dockerdemoapi:latest

        ports:

        - containerPort: 80

      - name: inventorydb

        image: &lt;your docker hub namespace&gt;/inventorydb:latest

        ports:

        - containerPort: 1433

1. Deploy to AKS:

$ kubectrl apply -f dockerdemo.yml

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

You should be able to see the Kubernetes pods, etc, deploying via the UI – the images are being pulled from Docker Hub:

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

1. Request a load balancer setup so that we can expose the API on the internet:

$ kubectl

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Get the list of running services, as shown above – you should see that there is an IP address being applied to the &quot;dockerdemo-deployment&quot; (as above). This takes a little while to apply.

$ kubectl get services

1. All going well you should be able to see a result in our &quot;/api/values&quot; and &quot;/api/database&quot; endpoints.
